I got him from my brother, and only parted with him because William's stock was gone. He had to the end of lifea simplicity which was quite touching. One summer day-a dog-day·— when all dogs found straying were hauled away to the police-office, and killed off in twenties with strychnine, I met Puck trotting along Princes Street with a policeman, a rope round his neck, he look- ing up in the fatal, official, but kindly countenance in the most artless and cheerful manner, wagging his tail and trotting along. In ten minutes he would have been in the next world; for I am one of those who believe dogs bavea next world, and why not? Puck ended his days as the best dog in Roxburghshire. Placide quiescas!
